{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491322"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"913"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/913"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.38,0.04,0.18,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82988"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/913"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68048"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"361"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28397"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82988"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of aching in his left calf. These symptoms appear when he walks more than 200 metres and settle when he rests. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and has type II diabetes. He takes metformin and atenolol. A recent serum creatinine was 150 \u00b5mol/L (60-110). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. Examination of his right leg and its pulses is normal. On the left side, the femoral artery pulse is diminished and the distal pulses cannot be felt. His ankle-brachial index is 0.8 on the right and 0.6 on the left. He is started on aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duplex ultrasonography","Lifestyle modification and graded exercise program","Standard angiography","CT angiography","MR angiography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has several clear cardiovascular risk factors and provides a typical history of peripheral arterial disease. The key to this question is the risk of the patient based on the ABI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ankle-brachial index of less than 0.9 confirms the presence of peripheral artery disease. The patient\u0027s symptoms represent claudication and there seems to be no evidence of chronic limb-threatening ischaemia (rest pain or tissue loss). The symptoms are not severe enough to require invasive intervention of his arterial disease, but it is appropriate to reduce the risk of cardiovascular events by starting an antiplatelet agent. Cardiovascular risk factor management, optimising diabetes management, and a supervised \u003Cstrong\u003Eexercise program\u003C/strong\u003E should be the key principles of management. He does not require any form of imaging at this stage. He will need to be kept under regular surveillance, and should his symptoms or his ankle-brachial index worsen, then imaging of the arterial tree can be considered. His renal dysfunction would be a significant concern if arterial imaging with CT angiography or invasive angiography were to be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuplex ultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-invasive imaging technique that can be used to assess blood flow and identify blockages in the arteries. However, in this case, the diagnosis of peripheral artery disease is already confirmed by the ankle-brachial index, and the initial management should focus on lifestyle modification and exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStandard angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that involves injecting contrast dye into the arteries to visualize blockages. It is not indicated at this stage, as the patient does not have critical limb ischaemia or severe symptoms that would warrant surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EMR angiography\u003C/strong\u003E are advanced imaging techniques that provide detailed images of the blood vessels. These are not necessary at this point, as the patient\u0027s condition can be managed with non-invasive measures. Additionally, the patient\u0027s renal dysfunction poses a risk for contrast-induced nephropathy with CT angiography.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lifestyle issues and exercise management should be considered in all patients with peripheral artery disease.","An ankle-brachial index of less than 0.9 confirms the presence of peripheral artery disease.","Initial management of claudication includes lifestyle modification and a supervised exercise program."],"references":["Willner, S. The Role of Imaging in Peripheral Arterial Disease. In: Sareen, N, Ojha, A, editors. Peripheral Arterial Disease: A practical approach. 1st ed. InTechOpen; 2018.","Brass EP, Hiatt WR. Aspirin Monotherapy Should Not Be Recommended for Cardioprotection in Patients With Symptomatic Peripheral Artery Disease. Circulation. 2017 Aug 29;136(9):785-786. doi: 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.117.028888. PMID: 28847795. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28847795/","Bhagirath VC, Nash D, Wan D, Anand SS. Building Your Peripheral Artery Disease Toolkit: Medical Management of Peripheral Artery Disease in 2022. Can J Cardiol. 2022 May;38(5):634-644. doi: 10.1016/j.cjca.2022.02.004. Epub 2022 Feb 10. PMID: 35151781. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35151781/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68048"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"913"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68048"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T21:07:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T21:07:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"913"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82988"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https:/